Hi, what is the (right) way to set the window position/location in a WindowsGL project?

For instance, in a DX project i use:
            var screen = System.Windows.Forms.Screen.AllScreens.First(e => e.Primary); 
            System.Drawing.Rectangle rect = screen.Bounds;
            //Window.IsBorderless = true;
            Window.Position = new Point(rect.Width / 2 - 640, rect.Height / 2 - 360);

For a GL project, i used to use:
            // Use reflection to center the window on screen.
            OpenTK.GameWindow window = null;
            Type type = typeof(OpenTKGameWindow);
            FieldInfo field = type.GetField("window", BindingFlags.NonPublic | BindingFlags.Instance);
            if (field != null)
            {
                window = (OpenTK.GameWindow)field.GetValue(this.Window);

```
            window.Location = new System.Drawing.Point(
                (window.Location.X + 320) - 640,
                (window.Location.Y + 240) - 360
                );

            window.WindowBorder = OpenTK.WindowBorder.Hidden;
        }
```

That was working like a charm 'till 3.3 (or 3.2?), so i wander what's the new way for such a simple but crucial task?

Thanks, Greg.
